## `repositories/` — Repository Interfaces (`*.repository.ts`)

Contract only — no Prisma types, no `@Injectable`. Implementation lives in `infrastructure/`.

**DDD rule: Repositories exist ONLY for Aggregate Roots.**

Giving a child entity its own repository breaks the consistency boundary — it can be mutated independently, bypassing the root's invariant checks.

```
✅ Correct                              ❌ Wrong
  OrderRepository → Order (root)          OrderItemRepository → OrderItem
    └── OrderItem  (no repository)          ← bypasses Order's invariants
```

**If an object needs its own repository, it IS an Aggregate Root — by definition.**

| Situation | Base class | Repository? |
|---|---|---|
| Root of its own consistency boundary | `AggregateRoot<T>` | ✅ Yes |
| Root, domain events not yet needed | `BaseDomain<T>` | ✅ Yes — add events when behaviour grows |
| Child entity inside an aggregate | `BaseDomain<T>` | ❌ No — load via the root |

**Token naming rule — Symbol name = interface name** (one import = both token and type):

```ts
// ✅ GOOD — one import serves as @Inject() token AND type annotation
export const IOrderRepository = Symbol('IOrderRepository');

export interface IOrderRepository
  extends IRepository<Order, string, OrderFilter> {
  // Only methods BEYOND standard CRUD
  findByCustomerId(customerId: string): Promise<Order[]>;
}
// IRepository already provides: findById / findAll / findPaged / create / update / delete / count

// ❌ BAD — two separate names, easy to mismatch
export const ORDER_REPOSITORY = Symbol('ORDER_REPOSITORY');
export interface IOrderRepository extends IRepository<...> { ... }
```

